answers.body_markdown:
It&#39;s pretty simple if you use your machine&#39;s [date](http://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/date.1.html) command. However, to do this, you&#39;ll need to call the system command from your NodeJS script. That is possible with NodeJS&#39;s `exec` command. You can read more about it [here](https://stackoverflow.com/a/20643568/1913185). It&#39;s basically a way to call system function from inside your NodeJS code. It runs asyncronous, so it requires a callback that has NodeJS `error`, `stdout`, and `stderror`.

    const { exec } = require(&#39;child_process&#39;);

    const timestamp = &#39;20190927 10:00:00&#39;;

    exec(`/bin/date --set=&quot;${timestamp}&quot;`, (err, stdout, stderr) =&gt; {
      if (err || stderr) {
        console.error(err);
        console.log(stderr);
      } else {
        console.log(stdout);
        console.log(`Successfully set the system&#39;s datetime to ${stdout}`);
      }
    }));

Likely you won&#39;t have a `$PATH` available. Therefore, you&#39;ll need to specify the exact path to date. You can find that by running `which date` in a terminal and copying the output into the `exac` statement. For my Ubuntu 18.04 machine, it&#39;s located in `/bin/date`.

