Mateus&#39; answer does a good job describing how to setup your controller function to return the PDF file. I would do something like this in your `/routes/web.php` file:

```
Route::get(&#39;/show-pdf/{id}&#39;, function($id) {
    $file = YourFileModel::find($id);
    return response()-&gt;file(storage_path($file-&gt;path));
})-&gt;name(&#39;show-pdf&#39;);
```

The other part of your question is how to embed the PDF in your `*.blade.php` view template. For this, I recommend using [PDFObject][1]. This is a dead simple PDF viewer JavaScript package that makes embedding PDFs easy.

If you are using `npm`, you can run `npm install pdfobject -S` to install this package. Otherwise, you can serve it from a [CDN][2], or host the script yourself. After including the script, you set it up like this:

**HTML**:
```
&lt;div id=&quot;pdf-viewer&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
```
**JS**:
```
&lt;script&gt;
PDFObject.embed(&quot;{{ route(&#39;show-pdf&#39;, [&#39;id&#39; =&gt; 1]) }}&quot;, &quot;#pdf-viewer&quot;);
&lt;/script&gt;
```
And that&#39;s it — super simple! And, in my opinion, it provides a nicer UX for your users than navigating to a page that shows the PDF all by itself. I hope you find this helpful!

---
**UPDATE:**
After reading your comments on the other answer, I thought you might find [this example][3] particularly useful for what you are trying to do.


  [1]: https://pdfobject.com/
  [2]: https://cdnjs.com/libraries/pdfobject/
  [3]: https://pdfobject.com/examples/replace-PDF-with-second-PDF.html

